  "phase_D_note": "Approach 3 (multiple affine pieces - upper half stretched differently from lower half) is excluded a priori: combining two affine pieces along a chord generically produces a kink at the join, breaking strict convexity. Even when the join points are coincident (continuous), the second-derivative discontinuity prevents the polygon from satisfying \"strict convexity\" in any meaningful sense for a polygon (corners would have undefined cross products). Additionally, vertices on opposite halves would no longer share a common scaling in their distance multisets, which is exactly what a single-axis stretch exploits.",
  "conclusion": "No 4-bad polygon found among affine-stretched regular n-gons for n in {12, 16, 18, 20, 24, 28, 32, 36, 40, 48}. Best result is n=24 at lam = 2/sqrt(3)-1 reproducing the known \u00a77.3 example with 6/24 vertices having multiplicity >= 4 (NOT a counterexample). Mathematical reason: the 1-parameter affine-stretch family imposes only one degree of freedom, but achieving multiplicity >= 4 simultaneously at all n vertices requires forcing many independent equality conditions. The \u00a77.3 example exploits a special coincidence at n=24, but this coincidence at lam = 2/sqrt(3) - 1 only saturates 6 of 24 orbits.",
